  "query": "What actions can be taken to mitigate the impacts of roads on amphibian populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from action documents indicates: Closing roads during seasonal amphibian migrations protected large numbers of amphibians from death at closure sites, including where combined with assisted crossings and barrier fences (842). Organizing human patrols to carry amphibians across roads moved large numbers (e.g., 7,532 toads before/after breeding to up to half a million annually; over 400 patrols, with one dataset noting 71 patrols averaging 90 person-hours and active up to 10 years), yet 64\u201370% of populations still declined over 6\u201310 years and at 7% of sites over 500 toads were still killed (784). Installing culverts/tunnels as road crossings reduced amphibian road deaths in six of seven studies (one only when barrier fencing was also installed), though one study found no effect; many studies documented use of culverts/tunnels by amphibians (e.g., 15\u201385% of individuals, 3\u201315 species, or 23\u2013100% of culverts used), while others reported mixed or low use, with use influenced by culvert diameter (wider used more), length (long avoided), lighting (mixed effects), substrate (natural favored), presence of water (mixed), entrance location, and tunnel climate; designs such as one-way vertical-entry chutes caused high mortality of common toads, steel culvert condensation had very high metal concentrations, and one study reported thousands of amphibians still killed on the road (884).",
